e.  Most of the messages in the first days and weeks are about the company.  Read the <a title=\"The First Minutes Count - HBS Working Knowledge\" href=\"http://hbswk.hbs.edu/item/7193.html?wknews=04032013\" target=\"_blank\">full article</a> in Working Knowledge, an online Harvard Business School publication, for  details on how Wipro determined how focusing on the individual resulted in more than 25 percent better retention than the traditional company-focused program.\n\n<em>The researchers are currently expanding the research.  If your company is interested in being part of a field study please write to Francesca Gino directly at <a href=\"mailto:fgino@hbs.edu\">fgino@hbs.edu</a>.</em>\n\n&nbsp;','The First Minutes Count (Harvard Research)','','inherit','open','open','','208-revision-3','','','2013-04-07 23:29:28','2013-04-07 23:29:28','',208,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/208-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(211,1,'2013-04-07 22:54:57','2013-04-07 22:54:57','One of the core Vimbli value propositions is \"new hire ownership\" of the transition.  We believe the individual is best positioned to execute the transition.  The company can support, but the individual needs to step-up and own the transition.\n\nRecent research published in Working Knowledge confirms the focus on the individual as an important driver of a successful onboarding.\n\nIn <a title=\"The First Minutes Count - HBS Working Knowledge\" href=\"http://hbswk.hbs.edu/item/7193.html?wknews=04032013\" target=\"_blank\"><em>First Minutes are Critical in New-Employee Orientation</em></a> Carmen Noble shares new research by Daniel M. Cable, Francesca Gino, and Bradley R. Staats.<strong></strong>\n\nHere is a short summary:  Many believe the first couple of months are key to new hire performance and engagement.  Few get it right. The research indicates companies focus too much on the company and not enough on the new hire.   Most of the message in the first couple of days and weeks are about the company this the company that.  Read the full article for  details on how Wipro determine the individual focus results in more than 25% better retention than the traditional company focused program.\n\nThe <a title=\"The First Minutes Count - HBS Working Knowledge\" href=\"http://hbswk.hbs.edu/item/7193.html?wknews=04032013\" target=\"_blank\">full article</a> is available in Working Knowledge, an online Harvard Business School publication.\n\n<em>The researchers are currently expanding the research.  If your company is interested in being part of a field study please write to Francesca Gino directly at <a href=\"mailto:fgino@hbs.edu\">fgino@hbs.edu</a>.</em>\n\n&nbsp;','The First Minutes Count (Harvard Research)','','inherit','open','open','','208-revision-2','','','2013-04-07 22:54:57','2013-04-07 22:54:57','',208,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/208-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(296,1,'2013-05-28 19:14:16','2013-05-28 19:14:16','The recent results from the Vimbli Onboarding survey is summarized in this report.  We hope the report will help you as you consider how to make the most of life\'s transitions.\r\n\r\nFor yourself, and also for those in your team / company.\r\n\r\n<a href=\"http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/vimbli-onboarding-report/vimbli-changing-onboarding-odds-survey-results-may-2013/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-292\">Vimbli - Changing Onboarding Odds - Survey R</a><a href=\"http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/vimbli-onboarding-report/vimbli-changing-onboarding-odds-survey-results-may-2013/\" rel=\"attachment wp-att-292\">esults May 2013</a>\r\n\r\nYour feedback is most welcome.\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','Vimbli Onboarding Report','','inherit','open','open','','291-revision-3','','','2013-05-28 19:14:16','2013-05-28 19:14:16','',291,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/291-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(190,1,'2013-03-29 16:32:06','2013-03-29 16:32:06','Vimbli exists to help you be more successful.\r\n\r\nOur goal is to increase your knowledge of yourself by being a partner on your life journey.  As you go through life there will be many transitions.  Our first solution addresses corporate transitions (think new job, new company, new boss).\r\n\r\nThe Vimbli solution uses your strengths, values and overall life goals as the starting point to navigate any transition.   Each transition is viewed as a learning opportunity, and is structured to allow you to achieve a successful outcome and to deepen your knowledge of yourself.\r\n\r\nWe have created an straightforward planning and execution framework:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li>Start with a view of what success looks like</li>\r\n	<li>Recruit a sponsor for your \"endeavour\", and share your view of success (Optional, but highly recommended)</li>\r\n	<li>Convert the \"success\" into the activities and relationships that will increase the probability of a successful outcome</li>\r\n	<li>Review progress and make adjustments throughout the transition (with your sponsor, as needed)</li>\r\n</ol>\r\nThese 4 elements are deceptively simple on paper, but extremely difficult in practice.  In order to make it as easy as possible we have developed a solution that automates most of the data capture and visualization.\r\n\r\nAt the core Vimbli integrates securely with your calendar, email and address book.  Currently we have Google (gmail and Google Apps) covered, we are working to add Microsoft Exchange.  In future we intend to add voice, IM and SMS as well.\r\n\r\nFor different roles Vimbli allows templates to give you a start to plan your our transition.  There is no short-cut on this piece you need to do the work to define what you want out the mission, what you will do to get it, and share the plan with your sponsor.\r\n\r\nCommunication with your sponsor is streamlined using personalized emails with your activity and goal information.  You own the update.  Before sharing it with your sponsor you have the opportunity to make edits to the content.  Yes you can add and delete.  What you share is your decision.\r\n\r\nWe have created Vimbli with you in mind.   The application will most likely live in the enterprise, but our intend is to serve individuals who want to live life to the full.\r\n\r\nThat is why we picked the name Vimbli.  A play on \"vim and vigor\", meaning \"a zest for life\".  We wanted to capture the energy involved in transitions and personal growth.  We are looking forward to have you on the journey with us.\r\n\r\nWhat would you like to see in a solution like Vimbli?  Let us know.','What is Vimbli?','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-9','','','2013-03-29 16:32:06','2013-03-29 16:32:06','',1,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/1-revision-9/',0,'revision','',0),(189,1,'2013-03-29 16:32:29','2013-03-29 16:32:29','Progress and personal growth does not happen without change.  Every moment of significant progress and personal growth is preceded by a transition of some sort.\r\n\r\nOften these transitions are traumatic, and can be somewhat painful.  A new job, a new city, a new company, a new relationship …\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_184\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-184   \" title=\"Your Vision\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Cathedralandtentviaistock-300x118.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"118\" /> What is your vision? Cathedral and/ or Tent ...[/caption]\r\n\r\nNo one transition looks the same, but successful transitions have common elements.  A successful transition requires a lot of effort and focus, but there are 5 common elements:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Your VISION</strong> of what success looks like:  Are you building cathedral, building a shack or pitching a tent.  Your answer will impact everything you do.  If you don’t have an answer you’ll probably need to buckle up for a bumpy ride ‘til you find the vision, and find the sponsor who shares the vision with you.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your PLAN</strong>, with building blocks:  Something worthwhile needs you to do a few things, and to do the things well.  What the things are often differ, but in most cases a transition requires building and maintaining relationships.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your Execution: </strong> Plans are great, but in the case of your own life you have to go and execute your plan.  Many other things in life you can get others to do for you.  Your life you have to live yourself.  Having others with you makes the journey more fun, but you need to do the living.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your R<span style=\"color: #000000;\">eflection</span>: </strong> Few plans actually work out as planned.  Hence the name, \"Plan\".  Reflecting on your progress (and where possible working with your sponsor and possibly some advisors and supporters) is critical.  Regular reflection allow you to identify what work and what does not.  In many ways that is what a journal done well achieves.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your Adjustments: </strong>Many people reflect, and reflect but never take action on the reflection.  Reflection impacts your plan in 2 ways.  You can decide something is working, and do more of it OR you can decide something is not working and make a change.  The latter catergory also includes achieved goals.  Celebrate your achievements. Celebrate your failures. Learn from it, make adjustments and move forward.  Sometimes the learning process takes a bit longer, and it is ok to give yourself time to complete the process.<strong>   </strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"line-height: 24px;\">\r\n</span></span><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Without the explicit commitment to do the reviews and adjustments you should not waste time on #1, #2 and #3.  Go and buy a lottery ticket instead.  Ok, maybe this is a bit harsh.  The truth is without Reflection on and Adjustments to your plan your life journey will be less complete.   Note that true reflection may lead you to opt to do less not more.  Each of us is unique.  You need to learn more about yourself, and live your life.  Just like I need to learn more about myself and live my life.  </span>\r\n\r\nYou read this and it sounds black and white you need to figure out where you want to add your own color.  The elements identified give only the starting point for you to create your own transition. You have to make adjustments to fit your worldview, personality and capabilities, and also align with the company culture and the immediate business needs.\r\n\r\nIn future posts we’ll cover the elements in detail and also discuss how to personalize the approach to fit you and your situation.\r\n\r\nIn the meantime – What is your secret to a successful transition? If you have different tips for different transitions feel free to share.','How to make change count!','','inherit','open','open','','80-revision-15','','','2013-03-29 16:32:29','2013-03-29 16:32:29','',80,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/80-revision-15/',0,'revision','',0),(188,1,'2013-03-29 16:19:57','2013-03-29 16:19:57','Progress and personal growth does not happen without change.  Every moment of significant progress and personal growth is preceded by a transition of some sort.\r\n\r\nOften these transitions are traumatic, and can be somewhat painful.  A new job, a new city, a new company, a new relationship …\r\n\r\n[caption id=\"attachment_184\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"300\"]<img class=\"size-medium wp-image-184   \" title=\"Your Vision\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Cathedralandtentviaistock-300x118.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"300\" height=\"118\" /> What is your vision? Cathedral and/ or Tent ...[/caption]\r\n\r\nNo one transition looks the same, but successful transitions have common elements.  A successful transition requires a lot of effort and focus, but there are 5 common elements:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Your VISION</strong> of what success looks like:  Are you building cathedral, building a shack or pitching a tent.  Your answer will impact everything you do.  If you don’t have an answer you’ll probably need to buckle up for a bumpy ride ‘til you find the vision, and find the sponsor who shares the vision with you.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your PLAN</strong>, with building blocks:  Something worthwhile needs you to do a few things, and to do the things well.  What the things are often differ, but in most cases a transition requires building and maintaining relationships.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your Execution: </strong> Plans are great, but in the case of your own life you have to go and execute your plan.  Many other things in life you can get others to do for you.  Your life you have to live yourself.  Having others with you makes the journey more fun, but you need to do the living.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your R<span style=\"color: #000000;\">eflection</span>: </strong> Few plans actually work out as planned.  Hence the name, \"Plan\".  Reflecting on your progress (and where possible working with your sponsor and possibly some advisors and supporters) is critical.  Regular reflection allow you to identify what work and what does not.  In many ways that is what a journal done well achieves.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your Adjustments: </strong>Many people reflect, and reflect but never take action on the reflection.  Reflection impacts your plan in 2 ways.  You can decide something is working, and do more of it OR you can decide something is not working and make a change.  The latter catergory also includes achieved goals.  Celebrate your achievements. Celebrate your failures. Learn from it, make adjustments and move forward.  Sometimes the learning process takes a bit longer, and it is ok to give yourself time to complete the process.<strong>   </strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"line-height: 24px;\">\r\n</span></span><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Without the explicit commitment to do the reviews and adjustments you should not waste time on #1, #2 and #3.  Go and buy a lottery ticket instead.  Ok, maybe this is a bit harsh.  The truth is without Reflection on and Adjustments to your plan your life journey will be less complete.   Note that true reflection may lead you to opt to do less not more.  Each of us is unique.  You need to learn more about yourself, and live your life.  Just like I need to learn more about myself and live my life.  </span>\r\n\r\nYou read this and it sounds black and white you need to figure out where you want to add your own color.  The elements identified give only the starting point for you to create your own transition. You have to make adjustments to fit your worldview, personality and capabilities, and also align with the company culture and the immediate business needs.\r\n\r\nIn future posts we’ll cover the elements in detail and also discuss how to personalize the approach to fit you and your situation.\r\n\r\nIn the meantime – What is your secret to a successful transition? If you have different tips for different transitions feel free to share.','How to make change count!','','inherit','open','open','','80-revision-14','','','2013-03-29 16:19:57','2013-03-29 16:19:57','',80,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/80-revision-14/',0,'revision','',0),(68,1,'2012-12-07 07:52:02','2012-12-07 07:52:02','','iStock_000005449225Large','','inherit','open','open','','istock_000005449225large-3','','','2012-12-07 07:52:02','2012-12-07 07:52:02','',0,'http://75.125.190.162:7427/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2012/12/iStock_000005449225Large1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(186,1,'2013-03-29 15:39:07','2013-03-29 15:39:07','Vimbli exists to help you be more successful.\r\n\r\nOur goal is to increase your knowledge of yourself by being a partner on your life journey.  As you go through life there will be many transitions.  Our first solution addresses corporate transitions (think new job, new company, new boss).\r\n\r\nThe Vimbli solution uses your strengths, values and overall life goals as the starting point to navigate any transition.   Each transition is viewed as a learning opportunity, and is structured to allow you to achieve a successful outcome and to deepen your knowledge of yourself.\r\n\r\nWe have created an straightforward planning and execution framework:\r\n\r\n1.  Start with a view of what success looks like \r\n\r\n2.  Recruit a sponsor for your \"endeavour\", and share your view of success (Optional, but highly recommended)\r\n\r\n2.  Convert the \"success\" into the activities and relationships that will increase the probability of a successful outcome\r\n\r\n3.  Review progress and make adjustments throughout the transition (with your sponsor, as needed)\r\n\r\nThese 3 elements are deceptively simple on paper, but extremely difficult to execute in practice.  In order to make it as easy as possible we have developed a solution that automates most of the data capture and visualization.\r\n\r\nAt the core Vimbli integrates securely with your calendar, email and address book.  Currently we have Google (gmail and Google Apps) covered, we are working to add Microsoft Exchange.  In future we intend to add voice, IM and SMS as well.\r\n\r\nFor different roles Vimbli allows templates to give you a start to plan your our transition.  There is no short-cut on this piece you need to do the work to define what you want out the mission, what you will do to get it, and share the plan with your sponsor.\r\n\r\nCommunication with your sponsor is streamlined using personalized emails with your activity and goal information.  You own the update.  Before sharing it with your sponsor you have the opportunity to make edits to the content.  Yes you can add and delete.  What you share is your decision.\r\n\r\nWe have created Vimbli with you in mind.   The application will most likely live in the enterprise, but our intend is to serve individuals who want to live life to the full.\r\n\r\nThat is why we picked the name Vimbli.  A play on \"vim and vigor\", meaning \"a zest for life\".  We wanted to capture the energy involved in transitions and personal growth.  We are looking forward to have you on the journey with us.\r\n\r\nWhat would you like to see in a solution like Vimbli?  Let us know.','What is Vimbli?','','inherit','open','open','','1-revision-7','','','2013-03-29 15:39:07','2013-03-29 15:39:07','',1,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/1-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(184,1,'2013-03-29 16:14:36','2013-03-29 16:14:36','When you think about your vision make it personal.  For some the cathedral is the answer, for some the tent ... and for some it will be something in between.','Your Vision','Cathedral and/ or Tent?','inherit','open','open','','cathedralandtentviaistock','','','2013-03-29 16:14:36','2013-03-29 16:14:36','',80,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/02/Cathedralandtentviaistock.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(185,1,'2013-03-29 16:05:36','2013-03-29 16:05:36','Progress and personal growth does not happen without change.  Every moment of significant progress and personal growth is preceded by a transition of some sort.\r\n\r\nOften these transitions are traumatic, and can be somewhat painful.  A new job, a new city, a new company, a new relationship …\r\n\r\nNo one transition looks the same, but successful transitions have common elements.  A successful transition requires a lot of effort and focus, but there are 5 common elements:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Your VISION</strong> of what success looks like:  Are you building cathedral, building a shack or pitching a tent.  Your answer will impact everything you do.  If you don’t have an answer you’ll probably need to buckle up for a bumpy ride ‘til you find the vision, and find the sponsor who shares the vision with you.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your PLAN</strong>, with building blocks:  Something worthwhile needs you to do a few things, and to do the things well.  What the things are often differ, but in most cases a transition requires building and maintaining relationships.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your Execution: </strong> Plans are great, but in the case of your own life you have to go and execute your plan.  Many other things in life you can get others to do for you.  Your life you have to live yourself.  Having others with you makes the journey more fun, but you need to do the living.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your R<span style=\"color: #000000;\">eflection</span>: </strong> Few plans actually work out as planned.  Hence the name, \"Plan\".  Reflecting on your progress (and where possible working with your sponsor and possibly some advisors and supporters) is critical.  Regular reflection allow you to identify what work and what does not.  In many ways that is what a journal done well achieves.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your Adjustments: </strong>Many people reflect, and reflect but never take action on the reflection.  Reflection impacts your plan in 2 ways.  You can decide something is working, and do more of it OR you can decide something is not working and make a change.  The latter catergory also includes achieved goals.  Celebrate your achievements. Celebrate your failures. Learn from it, make adjustments and move forward.  Sometimes the learning process takes a bit longer, and it is ok to give yourself time to complete the process.<strong>   </strong></li>\r\n</ol>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: medium;\"><span style=\"line-height: 24px;\">\r\n</span></span><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Without the explicit commitment to do the reviews and adjustments you should not waste time on #1, #2 and #3.  Go and buy a lottery ticket instead.  Ok, maybe this is a bit harsh.  The truth is without Reflection on and Adjustments to your plan your life journey will be less complete.   Note that true reflection may lead you to opt to do less not more.  Each of us is unique.  You need to learn more about yourself, and live your life.  Just like I need to learn more about myself and live my life.  </span>\r\n\r\nYou read this and it sounds black and white you need to figure out where you want to add your own color.  The elements identified give only the starting point for you to create your own transition. You have to make adjustments to fit your worldview, personality and capabilities, and also align with the company culture and the immediate business needs.\r\n\r\nIn future posts we’ll cover the elements in detail and also discuss how to personalize the approach to fit you and your situation.\r\n\r\nIn the meantime – What is your secret to a successful transition? If you have different tips for different transitions feel free to share.','How do make change count!','','inherit','open','open','','80-revision-13','','','2013-03-29 16:05:36','2013-03-29 16:05:36','',80,'http://vimbli.com/beta/app/webroot/blog/80-revision-13/',0,'revision','',0),(183,1,'2013-03-29 15:58:38','2013-03-29 15:58:38','Progress and personal growth does not happen without change.  Every moment of significant progress and personal growth is preceded by a transition of some sort.\r\n\r\nOften these transitions are traumatic, and can be somewhat painful.  A new job, a new city, a new company, a new relationship …\r\n\r\nNo one transition looks the same, but successful transitions have common elements.  A successful transition requires a lot of effort and focus, but there are 5 common elements:\r\n<ol>\r\n	<li><strong>Your VISION</strong> of what success looks like:  Are you building cathedral, building a shack or pitching a tent.  Your answer will impact everything you do.  If you don’t have an answer you’ll probably need to buckle up for a bumpy ride ‘til you find the vision, and find the sponsor who shares the vision with you.</li>\r\n	<li><strong>Your PLAN</strong>, with building blocks:  Something worthwhile needs you to do a few things, and to do the things well.  What the things are often differ, but in most cases a transition requi