s engaged their accountability contact with weekly updates were more likely to achieve success than those who did not reach out regularly.\n\n2.  Accountability: Those who made the commitment to someone specific were more likely to be successful than those who did not.\n\n3.  Written commitment:  Those who wrote down their commitment were more likely to be successful that those who did not.  Independent of them having an accountable person, or a regular engagement cadence.\n\nGetting someone to support you on your journey, and keeping up with regular updates could both be challenging, but you can write down your goals.  Why not?  If it makes you 50% more likely to achieve the goals ... let\'s get started!\n\n&nbsp;','How do you value written goals? Making sense of the Yale report ... ','','inherit','open','open','','359-revision-2','','','2013-06-14 18:18:42','2013-06-14 18:18:42','',359,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/359-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(362,1,'2013-06-14 18:20:04','2013-06-14 18:20:04','<a title=\"About - Michael Hyatt\" href=\"http://michaelhyatt.com/about\" target=\"_blank\">Michael Hyatt</a> recently posted a 101 on <a title=\"Michael Hyatt Goal Setting 101\" href=\"http://michaelhyatt.com/goal-setting.html\" target=\"_blank\">Goal Setting</a>.  If you are good at setting goals and realizing goals it is worth a read.  If you are so-so at achieving your goals it will definitely be a good return on your time to read the article.\n\nAt Vimbli we are excited about Michael\'s post as it supports the design of the solution we have put in place the help individuals make the most of professional transitions.  More on the Vimbli solution later.\n\nIn his post Michael refers to a report on the value of written goals, but he does not get deeper into the report.  The report is aligned with the Vimbli report on professional transitions.  The Vimbli report indicated people with personal plans are twice as likely to be top performers than those without.  