 evening, cold and gray,\nTo a chasm, vast, and deep, and wide,\nThrough which was flowing a sullen tide.\n\nThe old man crossed in the twilight dim;\nThe sullen stream had no fear for him;\nBut he turned, when safe on the other side,\nAnd built a bridge to span the tide.\n\n\"Old man,\" said a fellow pilgrim, near,\n\"You are wasting strength with building here;\nYour journey will end with the ending day;\nYou never again will pass this way;\nYou\'ve crossed the chasm, deep and wide-\nWhy build you this bridge at the evening tide?\"\n\nThe builder lifted his old gray head:\n\"Good friend, in the path I have come,\" he said,\n\"There followeth after me today,\nA youth, whose feet must pass this way.\n\nThis chasm, that has been naught to me,\nTo that fair-haired youth may a pitfall be.\nHe, too, must cross in the twilight dim;\nGood friend, I am building this bridge for him.\n\n<a title=\"Will Allen Dromgoole\" href=\"http://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Will_Allen_Dromgoole\">Will Allen Dromgoole</a>\n\n</div>','','','inherit','open','open','','413-revision','','','2013-06-26 00:34:58','2013-06-26 00:34:58','',413,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/413-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(415,1,'2013-06-26 02:52:15','0000-00-00 00:00:00','Differentiate between projects and you\r\n\r\nProjects you can delegate. You ... only you can live.\r\n\r\nManage the split\r\n\r\nFocus ...\r\n\r\nHolistic ... you are only one,\r\n\r\nBreak-it down\r\n\r\nExecute in sprints\r\n\r\nReview\r\n\r\nMake adjustments go again\r\n\r\n&nbsp;','How to make sense of all the happenings? ','','draft','open','open','','','','','2013-06-26 02:52:15','2013-06-26 02:52:15','',0,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/?p=415',0,'post','',0),(416,1,'2013-06-26 00:38:53','2013-06-26 00:38:53','Differentiate between projects and you\n\nProjects you can d\n\nFocus ...\n\nHolistic ... you are only one,\n\nBreak-it down\n\nExecute in sprints\n\nReview\n\nMake adjustments go again\n\n&nbsp;','How to make sense of all the happenings? ','','inherit','open','open','','415-revision','','','2013-06-26 00:38:53','2013-06-26 00:38:53','',415,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/415-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(417,1,'2013-06-26 00:40:31','2013-06-26 00:40:31','Differentiate between projects and you\n\nProjects you can delegate. You ... only you can live.\n\nManage the split\n\nFocus ...\n\nHolistic ... you are only one,\n\nBreak-it down\n\nExecute in sprints\n\nReview\n\nMake adjustments go again\n\n&nbsp;','How to make sense of all the happenings? ','','inherit','open','open','','415-revision-2','','','2013-06-26 00:40:31','2013-06-26 00:40:31','',415,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/415-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(420,1,'2013-07-04 14:46:01','2013-07-04 14:46:01','','Portugese soldiers - WW1','','inherit','open','open','','portugese-soldiers-ww1','','','2013-07-04 14:46:01','2013-07-04 14:46:01','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg',0,'attachment','image/jpeg',0),(421,1,'2013-07-04 14:48:11','2013-07-04 14:48:11','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-420\" title=\"Portugese soldiers - WW1\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" />\n\nLife happens and sometimes we have to wait.  Either for something to happen, somebody to show up, or just for personal inspiration.\n\nI found that if I take an active approach to waiting the wait time is often very valuable, and in most cases enjoyable.  When I don\'t take an active approach.  Well, let\'s just say the outcomes are often sub-optimal.\n\nI developed a 4 step approach to make my waits more active, for the lack of a better term \"3 Keys of Active Waiting\".\n<h3>1. Know why you are waiting.</h3>\nThis sounds obvious, but in many cases the waiting is an option.  Instead of waiting for the bus you can walk to the next bus stop, that cut back the wait time and add to your exercise time.  In some cases you are stuck with some waiting time.  And if you are at the DMV it could be a long wait.\n<h3>2.  Get to know fellow \"waiters\"</h3>\nMost likely you are not waiting alone.  Take the time to get to know some of the people waiting with you.\n<h3>3.  Take action on things you want to do, but never get to</h3>\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Your wait could be short, in which case you feel you cannot do anything productive.  Or it could be long, but you cannot work on that work sensitive material.  This \"key\" suggest you need to have a range of things you address in any given wait period.  Note that this key focus on things you can take action on.  It specifically avoid \"consumption\" of content.  Patience. </span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Less than 5 minutes?   Send a note to someone celebrating a birthday, send an invitation for coffee to a friend, jot down your thoughts related to a meeting later in the day, clean-up email subscriptions, ... </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">30 minutes?  Draft a new document, review a proposal, clean-up your inbox, carry a couple of stamped postcards with you and send friends written notes, make phone calls ... </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">More than an hour?  Mix-and-match the 30 minute elements, with shorter elements.   </span></li>\n</ul>\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">4.  Consume content</span></h3>\nLastly, after I have exhausted my options in 1 and 2 I\'ll switch to consumption of content.  People watching, reading, catching up on emails and Linkedin, and if I really have time ... check Facebook.\n\n&nbsp;\n\n&nbsp;\n\nPhoto:  Courtesy <a title=\"Portugese Soldiers WW1\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nlscotland/4699288263/\" target=\"_blank\">National Library of Scotland</a>, via Flickr.','Four Keys to Active Waiting','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision','','','2013-07-04 14:48:11','2013-07-04 14:48:11','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/419-revision/',0,'revision','',0),(422,1,'2013-07-04 14:48:44','2013-07-04 14:48:44','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-420\" title=\"Portugese soldiers - WW1\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" />\r\n\r\nLife happens and sometimes we have to wait.  Either for something to happen, somebody to show up, or just for personal inspiration.\r\n\r\nI found that if I take an active approach to waiting the wait time is often very valuable, and in most cases enjoyable.  When I don\'t take an active approach.  Well, let\'s just say the outcomes are often sub-optimal.\r\n\r\nI developed a 4 step approach to make my waits more active, for the lack of a better term \"3 Keys of Active Waiting\".\r\n<h3>1. Know why you are waiting.</h3>\r\nThis sounds obvious, but in many cases the waiting is an option.  Instead of waiting for the bus you can walk to the next bus stop, that cut back the wait time and add to your exercise time.  In some cases you are stuck with some waiting time.  And if you are at the DMV it could be a long wait.\r\n<h3>2.  Get to know fellow \"waiters\"</h3>\r\nMost likely you are not waiting alone.  Take the time to get to know some of the people waiting with you.\r\n<h3>3.  Take action on things you want to do, but never get to</h3>\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Your wait could be short, in which case you feel you cannot do anything productive.  Or it could be long, but you cannot work on that work sensitive material.  This \"key\" suggest you need to have a range of things you address in any given wait period.  Note that this key focus on things you can take action on.  It specifically avoid \"consumption\" of content.  Patience. </span>\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Less than 5 minutes?   Send a note to someone celebrating a birthday, send an invitation for coffee to a friend, jot down your thoughts related to a meeting later in the day, clean-up email subscriptions, ... </span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">30 minutes?  Draft a new document, review a proposal, clean-up your inbox, carry a couple of stamped postcards with you and send friends written notes, make phone calls ... </span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">More than an hour?  Mix-and-match the 30 minute elements, with shorter elements.   </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<h3><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">4.  Consume content</span></h3>\r\nLastly, after I have exhausted my options in 1 and 2 I\'ll switch to consumption of content.  People watching, reading, catching up on emails and Linkedin, and if I really have time ... check Facebook.\r\n\r\nWhat do you do when you have to wait?\r\n\r\n&nbsp;\r\n\r\nPhoto:  Courtesy <a title=\"Portugese Soldiers WW1\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nlscotland/4699288263/\" target=\"_blank\">National Library of Scotland</a>, via Flickr.','Four Keys to Active Waiting','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-2','','','2013-07-04 14:48:44','2013-07-04 14:48:44','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/419-revision-2/',0,'revision','',0),(423,1,'2013-07-04 14:52:02','2013-07-04 14:52:02','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-420\" title=\"Portugese soldiers - WW1\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" />\n\nLife happens and sometimes we have to wait.  Either for something to happen, somebody to show up, or just for personal inspiration.\n\nI found that if I take an active approach to waiting the wait time is often very valuable, and in most cases enjoyable.  When I don\'t take an active approach.  Well, let\'s just say the outcomes are often sub-optimal.\n\nI developed a 4 step approach to make my waits more active, for the lack of a better term \"3 Keys of Active Waiting\".\n\n<strong>1. Know why you are waiting ... </strong>\n\nThis sounds obvious, but in many cases the waiting is an option.  Instead of waiting for the bus you can walk to the next bus stop, that cut back the wait time and add to your exercise time.  In some cases you are stuck with some waiting time.  And if you are at the DMV it could be a long wait.\n\n<strong>2.  Get to know fellow \"waiters\" ...</strong>\n\nMost likely you are not waiting alone.  Take the time to get to know some of the people waiting with you.\n\n<strong>3.  Take action on things on your list ... </strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Your wait could be short, in which case you feel you cannot do anything productive.  Or it could be long, but you cannot work on that work sensitive material.  This \"key\" suggest you need to have a range of things you address in any given wait period.  Note that this key focus on things you can take action on.  It specifically avoid \"consumption\" of content.  Patience. </span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Less than 5 minutes?   Send a note to someone celebrating a birthday, send an invitation for coffee to a friend, jot down your thoughts related to a meeting later in the day, clean-up email subscriptions, ... </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">30 minutes?  Draft a new document, review a proposal, clean-up your inbox, carry a couple of stamped postcards with you and send friends written notes, make phone calls ... </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">More than an hour?  Mix-and-match the 30 minute elements, with shorter elements.   </span></li>\n</ul>\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">4.  Consume content ... </span></strong>\n\nLastly, after I have exhausted my options in 1 and 2 I\'ll switch to consumption of content.  People watching, reading, catching up on emails and Linkedin, and if I really have time ... check Facebook.\n\nWhat do you do when you have to wait?\n\n&nbsp;\n\nPhoto:  Courtesy <a title=\"Portugese Soldiers WW1\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nlscotland/4699288263/\" target=\"_blank\">National Library of Scotland</a>, via Flickr.','Four Keys to Active Waiting','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-3','','','2013-07-04 14:52:02','2013-07-04 14:52:02','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/419-revision-3/',0,'revision','',0),(424,1,'2013-07-17 19:38:20','2013-07-17 19:38:20','[caption id=\"attachment_404\" align=\"aligncenter\" width=\"604\"]<img class=\"size-full wp-image-404\" title=\"Hennie Junior and Senior, 1973? Isilimela.  Transkei. South Africa. \" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/6733_109417881614_5502440_n-002.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"604\" height=\"402\" /> 1973? Isilimela. Transkei. South Africa.[/caption]\n\nThanks to all responses!  My wife liked this comment a lot: <strong>Don\'t volunteer yourself to do what she \'asks\' you to do. Do it before she asks. </strong>\n\nThe detail responses make for <a title=\"Dad survey - June 2013\" href=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Dad-plan-Survey-Results-June-23.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">a good read</a> as dad-to-be, and I expect parents in general will enjoy reading it.  The range of responses is wide. You\'ll find things you like, and things you laugh at! and you\'ll probably have a good discussion with your partner on why you decided on your approach (and why you are/ were right!).\n\nThe summary of the \"research\" effort is:\n<ol>\n	<li>The change is personal.  You need to figure it out yourself.</li>\n	<li>Most agree on the following to do\'s  Create time for the mom, and be a true partner.   How you do it is up to you.</li>\n</ol>\nIn the written responses there are several gems. Here are a few:\n<ul>\n	<li>Accepting the fact that this is truly FOR LIFE!    Nothing that you have done will have as big an impact on your life.  Your kids remains your kids for the rest of your life...</li>\n	<li>It was all a blur. Got home with baby and thought: \"Now what!? Help!\".</li>\n	<li>No \"markers.\" it\'s a journey, not a destination.</li>\n	<li>One job at a time.  Keep yourself from thinking about the child in the aggregate - you\'ll go crazy.</li>\n	<li>...enjoy the ride, and always remember that the child isn\'t really yours...but rather us simply \"on loan\" from the Father above!</li>\n	<li>Kids spell love like this: TIME</li>\n	<li>Be sure to find time to focus on you as a couple. The kid(s) will move out but you will be together so you need to continuously invest in your relationship as a couple.</li>\n	<li>Enjoy the moment. It is fleeting. And don\'t panic! Babies are far more resilient than we give them credit for.</li>\n	<li>Being a father is the best job I have ever had.</li>\n</ul>\nDownload the cleaned-up responses <a title=\"Dad survey - June 2013\" href=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/06/Dad-plan-Survey-Results-June-23.pdf\" target=\"_blank\">here</a>.\n\n&nbsp;','Wisdom from Dads ... for dads ','','inherit','open','open','','400-autosave','','','2013-07-17 19:38:20','2013-07-17 19:38:20','',400,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/400-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(425,1,'2013-07-04 17:06:36','2013-07-04 17:06:36','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-420\" title=\"Portugese soldiers - WW1\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" />\n\nLife happens and sometimes we have to wait.  Either for something to happen, somebody to show up, or just for personal inspiration.\n\nI found that if I take an active approach to waiting the wait time is often very valuable, and in most cases enjoyable.  When I don\'t take an active approach.  Well, let\'s just say the outcomes are often sub-optimal.\n\nI developed a 4 step approach to make my waits more active, for the lack of a better term \"3 Keys of Active Waiting\".\n\n<strong>1. Know why you are waiting ... </strong>\n\nThis sounds obvious, but in many cases waiting is an option.  Instead of waiting for the bus you can walk to the next bus stop, that cut back the wait time and add to your exercise time.  In some cases you are stuck with some waiting time.  If you are at the DMV it could be a long and frustrating wait ...\n\n<strong>2.  Get to know fellow \"waiters\" ...</strong>\n\nMost likely you are not waiting alone.  Take the time to get to know some of the people waiting with you.  This is the step I am most likely to skip, but I often find this to be the most rewarding use of my time.  Keep in mind s/he is just as frustrated by the wait as you, and if not it will be interesting to know why they are not annoyed by the wait.\n\n<strong>3.  Take action on things on your list ... </strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Your wait could be short, in which case you feel you cannot do anything productive.  Or it could be long, but you cannot work on that work sensitive material.  This \"key\" suggest you need to have a range of things you address in any given wait period.  Note the focus on creating and sharing.  Avoid \"consumption\" of content.  Patience. :) </span>\n\nDon\'t know where to start?  A few ideas\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Less than 5 minutes?   Send a note to someone celebrating a birthday, send an invitation for coffee to a friend, jot down your thoughts related to a meeting later in the day, clean-up email subscriptions, ... </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">30 minutes?  Draft a new document, review a proposal, clean-up your inbox, carry a couple of stamped postcards with you and send friends written notes, make phone calls ... </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">More than an hour?  Mix-and-match the 30 minute elements, with shorter elements.   </span></li>\n</ul>\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">4.  Consume content, including people watching ... </span></strong>\n\nLastly, after I have exhausted my options in 1 and 2 I\'ll switch to consumption of content.  People watching, reading, catching up on emails and Linkedin, and if I really have time ... check Facebook.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">What do you do when you have to wait?</span>\n\nPhoto:  Courtesy <a title=\"Portugese Soldiers WW1\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nlscotland/4699288263/\" target=\"_blank\">National Library of Scotland</a>, via Flickr.  <span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Original title: \'OFFICIAL PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN ON THE BRITISH WESTERN FRONT. Portuguese in the trenches. A letter home.</span>','Waiting? 4 Thn','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-4','','','2013-07-04 17:06:36','2013-07-04 17:06:36','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/419-revision-4/',0,'revision','',0),(426,1,'2013-07-04 17:14:16','2013-07-04 17:14:16','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-420\" title=\"Portugese soldiers - WW1\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" />\n\nLife happens and sometimes we have to wait.  Either for something to happen, somebody to show up, or just for personal inspiration.\n\nI found that if I take an active approach to waiting the time is often very valuable, and in most cases enjoyable.  When I don\'t take an active approach.  Well, let\'s just say the outcomes are often sub-optimal ...\n\nI take a 4 step approach to make my waits more active.  Below are the four.  Let me know what you do to make the most the time you spend waiting.\n\n<strong>1. Know why you are waiting ... </strong>\n\nThis sounds obvious, but in many cases waiting is an option.  Instead of waiting for the bus you can walk to the next bus stop, that cut back the wait time and add to your exercise time.  In some cases you are stuck with some waiting time.  If you are at the DMV it could be a long and frustrating wait ...\n\n<strong>2.  Get to know fellow \"waiters\" ...</strong>\n\nMost likely you are not waiting alone.  Take the time to get to know some of the people waiting with you.  This is the step I am most likely to skip, but I often find this to be the most rewarding use of my time.  Keep in mind s/he is just as frustrated by the wait as you, and if not it will be interesting to know why they are not annoyed by the wait.\n\n<strong>3.  Take action on things on your list ... </strong>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Your wait could be short, in which case you feel you cannot do anything productive.  Or it could be long, but you cannot work on that work sensitive material.  There could be several excuses not to take actions.  If you have a ready list of things you can do in various situations the excuses become less relevant, and it is easier to break free from inertia.</span>\n\nDon\'t know where to start?  A few ideas\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Less than 5 minutes?   Send a note to someone celebrating a birthday, send an invitation for coffee to a friend, jot down your thoughts related to a meeting later in the day, clean-up email subscriptions, ... </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">30 minutes?  Draft a new document, review a proposal, clean-up your inbox, carry a couple of stamped postcards with you and send friends written notes, make phone calls ... </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">More than an hour?  Mix-and-match the 30 minute elements, with shorter elements.   </span></li>\n</ul>\n<div><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">Note the focus on creating and sharing.  Avoid \"consumption\" of content.  Patience. :) </span></div>\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">4.  Consume content, including people watching ... </span></strong>\n\nLastly, after I have exhausted my options in 1, 2 and 3 I\'ll switch to consumption of content.  People watching, reading, catching up on emails and LinkedIn, and if I really have time ... check Facebook.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">What do you do when you have to wait?</span>\n\nHennie\n\nFounder, Vimbli\n\nPhoto:  Courtesy <a title=\"Portugese Soldiers WW1\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nlscotland/4699288263/\" target=\"_blank\">National Library of Scotland</a>, via Flickr.  <span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Original title: \'OFFICIAL PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN ON THE BRITISH WESTERN FRONT. Portuguese in the trenches. A letter home.</span>','Four Keys to Better Waiting','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-5','','','2013-07-04 17:14:16','2013-07-04 17:14:16','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/419-revision-5/',0,'revision','',0),(427,1,'2013-07-04 17:16:40','2013-07-04 17:16:40','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-420\" title=\"Portugese soldiers - WW1\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" />\n\nLife happens and sometimes we have to wait.  Either for something to happen, somebody to show up, or just for personal inspiration.\n\nI found that if I take an active approach to waiting the time is often very valuable, and in most cases enjoyable.  When I don\'t take an active approach.  Well, let\'s just say the outcomes are often sub-optimal ...\n\nI take a 4 step approach to make the most of waiting time. Below are the four.  Let me know what you do to make the most the time you spend waiting.\n\n<strong>1. Know why you are waiting ... </strong>\n\nThis sounds obvious, but in many cases waiting is an option.  Instead of waiting for the bus you can walk to the next bus stop, that cut back the wait time and add to your exercise time.  In some cases you are stuck with some waiting time.  If you are at the DMV it could be a 