d 3 I\'ll switch to consumption of content.  People watching, reading, catching up on emails and LinkedIn, and if I really have time ... check Facebook.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">What do you do when you have to wait?</span>\n\nHennie\n\nFounder, Vimbli\n\nPhoto:  Courtesy <a title=\"Portugese Soldiers WW1\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nlscotland/4699288263/\" target=\"_blank\">National Library of Scotland</a>, via Flickr.  <span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Original title: \'OFFICIAL PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN ON THE BRITISH WESTERN FRONT. Portuguese in the trenches. A letter home.</span>','Four Keys to Better Waiting','','inherit','open','open','','419-autosave','','','2013-07-04 17:16:40','2013-07-04 17:16:40','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/419-autosave/',0,'revision','',0),(428,1,'2013-07-04 17:15:09','2013-07-04 17:15:09','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-420\" title=\"Portugese soldiers - WW1\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" />\r\n\r\nLife happens and sometimes we have to wait.  Either for something to happen, somebody to show up, or just for personal inspiration.\r\n\r\nI found that if I take an active approach to waiting the time is often very valuable, and in most cases enjoyable.  When I don\'t take an active approach.  Well, let\'s just say the outcomes are often sub-optimal ...\r\n\r\nI take a 4 step approach to make the most of waiting time. Below are the four.  Let me know what you do to make the most the time you spend waiting.\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Know why you are waiting ... </strong>\r\n\r\nThis sounds obvious, but in many cases waiting is an option.  Instead of waiting for the bus you can walk to the next bus stop, that cut back the wait time and add to your exercise time.  In some cases you are stuck with some waiting time.  If you are at the DMV it could be a long and frustrating wait ...\r\n\r\n<strong>2.  Get to know fellow \"waiters\" ...</strong>\r\n\r\nMost likely you are not waiting alone.  Take the time to get to know some of the people waiting with you.  This is the step I am most likely to skip, but I often find this to be the most rewarding use of my time.  Keep in mind s/he is just as frustrated by the wait as you, and if not it will be interesting to know why they are not annoyed by the wait.\r\n\r\n<strong>3.  Take action on things on your list ... </strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Your wait could be short, in which case you feel you cannot do anything productive.  Or it could be long, but you cannot work on that work sensitive material.  There could be several excuses not to take actions.  If you have a ready list of things you can do in various situations the excuses become less relevant, and it is easier to break free from inertia.</span>\r\n\r\nDon\'t know where to start?  A few ideas\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Less than 5 minutes?   Send a note to someone celebrating a birthday, send an invitation for coffee to a friend, jot down your thoughts related to a meeting later in the day, clean-up email subscriptions, ... </span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">30 minutes?  Draft a new document, review a proposal, clean-up your inbox, carry a couple of stamped postcards with you and send friends written notes, make phone calls ... </span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">More than an hour?  Mix-and-match the 30 minute elements, with shorter elements.   </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">Note the focus on creating and sharing.  Avoid \"consumption\" of content.  Patience. :) </span></div>\r\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">4.  Consume content, including people watching ... </span></strong>\r\n\r\nLastly, after I have exhausted my options in 1, 2 and 3 I\'ll switch to consumption of content.  People watching, reading, catching up on emails and LinkedIn, and if I really have time ... check Facebook.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">What do you do when you have to wait?</span>\r\n\r\nHennie\r\n\r\nFounder, Vimbli\r\n\r\nPhoto:  Courtesy <a title=\"Portugese Soldiers WW1\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nlscotland/4699288263/\" target=\"_blank\">National Library of Scotland</a>, via Flickr.  <span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Original title: \'OFFICIAL PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN ON THE BRITISH WESTERN FRONT. Portuguese in the trenches. A letter home.</span>','Four Keys to Better Waiting','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-6','','','2013-07-04 17:15:09','2013-07-04 17:15:09','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/419-revision-6/',0,'revision','',0),(429,1,'2013-07-04 17:59:48','2013-07-04 17:59:48','<img class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-420\" title=\"Portugese soldiers - WW1\" src=\"http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/wp-content/uploads/2013/07/Portugese-soldiers-WW1.jpg\" alt=\"\" width=\"600\" height=\"415\" />\r\n\r\nLife happens and sometimes we have to wait.  Either for something to happen, somebody to show up, or just for personal inspiration.\r\n\r\nI found that if I take an active approach to waiting the time is often very valuable, and in most cases enjoyable.  When I don\'t take an active approach.  Well, let\'s just say the outcomes are often sub-optimal ...\r\n\r\nI take a 4 step approach to make the most of waiting time. Below are the four.  Let me know what you do to make the most the time you spend waiting.\r\n\r\n<strong>1. Know why you are waiting ... </strong>\r\n\r\nThis sounds obvious, but in many cases waiting is an option.  Instead of waiting for the bus you can walk to the next bus stop, that cut back the wait time and add to your exercise time.  In some cases you are stuck with some waiting time.  If you are at the DMV it could be a long and frustrating wait ...\r\n\r\n<strong>2.  Get to know fellow \"waiters\" ...</strong>\r\n\r\nMost likely you are not waiting alone.  Take the time to get to know some of the people waiting with you.  This is the step I am most likely to skip, but I often find this to be the most rewarding use of my time.  Keep in mind s/he is just as frustrated by the wait as you, and if not it will be interesting to know why they are not annoyed by the wait.\r\n\r\n<strong>3.  Take action on things on your list ... </strong>\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Your wait could be short, in which case you feel you cannot do anything productive.  Or it could be long, but you cannot work on that work sensitive material.  There could be several excuses not to take actions.  If you have a ready list of things you can do in various situations the excuses become less relevant, and it is easier to break free from inertia.</span>\r\n\r\nDon\'t know where to start?  A few ideas\r\n<ul>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Less than 5 minutes?   Send a note to someone celebrating a birthday, send an invitation for coffee to a friend, jot down your thoughts related to a meeting later in the day, clean-up email subscriptions, ... </span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">30 minutes?  Draft a new document, review a proposal, clean-up your inbox, carry a couple of stamped postcards with you and send friends written notes, make phone calls ... </span></li>\r\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">More than an hour?  Mix-and-match the 30 minute elements, with shorter elements.   </span></li>\r\n</ul>\r\n<div><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">Note the focus on creating and sharing.  Avoid \"consumption\" of content.  Patience. :) </span></div>\r\n<strong><span style=\"font-size: 15.555556297302246px; line-height: 26.666667938232422px;\">4.  Consume content, including people watching ... </span></strong>\r\n\r\nLastly, after I have exhausted my options in 1, 2 and 3 I\'ll switch to consumption of content.  People watching, reading, catching up on emails and LinkedIn, and if I really have time ... check Facebook.\r\n\r\n<span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">What do you do when you have to wait?</span>\r\n\r\nHennie\r\n\r\nFounder, Vimbli\r\n\r\nPhoto:  Courtesy <a title=\"Portugese Soldiers WW1\" href=\"http://www.flickr.com/photos/nlscotland/4699288263/\" target=\"_blank\">National Library of Scotland</a>, via Flickr.  <span style=\"font-size: 16px;\">Original title: \'OFFICIAL PHOTOGRAPHS TAKEN ON THE BRITISH WESTERN FRONT. Portuguese in the trenches. A letter home.</span>','Four Keys to Better Waiting','','inherit','open','open','','419-revision-7','','','2013-07-04 17:59:48','2013-07-04 17:59:48','',419,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/419-revision-7/',0,'revision','',0),(430,1,'2013-07-10 19:29:04','0000-00-00 00:00:00','<span style=\"font-size: small;\">Several \"Strengths\" assessments exists.  We use a version of the strengths discussed in <a style=\"font-size: 16px;\" href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0195167015?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=joyday-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0195167015\"> Character Strengths and Virtues</a> by Peterson and Seligman.</span>\n\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">WISDOM &amp; KNOWLEDGE: Acquisition and use of knowledge</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Creativity [originality, ingenuity]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Curiosity [interest, novelty-seeking, openness to experience]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Open-mindedness [judgment, critical thinking]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Love of learning</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Perspective [wisdom]</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">COURAGE: Accomplish goals</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Bravery [valor]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Persistence [perseverance, industriousness]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Integrity [authenticity, honesty]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Vitality [zest, enthusiasm, vigor, energy]</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">HUMANITY: Tending and befriending others</span>\n<div>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Love</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Kindness [generosity, nurturance, care, compassion, altruistic love, \"niceness”]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Social intelligence [emotional intelligence, personal intelligence]</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">JUSTICE: Enable a healthy community life</span>\n<div>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Citizenship [social responsibility, loyalty, teamwork]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Fairness</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Leadership</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">TEMPERANCE: strengths that protect against excess</span>\n<div>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Forgiveness and mercy</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Humility / Modesty</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Prudence</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Self-regulation [self-control]</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">TRANSCENDANCE: connections to larger universe</span>\n<div>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Appreciation of beauty and excellence [awe, wonder, elevation]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Gratitude</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Hope [optimism, future-mindedness, future orientation]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Humor [playfulness]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Spirituality [religiousness, faith, purpose]</span></li>\n</ul>\n</div>\n<div><span style=\"font-size: small;\"> </span></div>\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">Other popular assessments include:</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">1.  Strengths Finder </span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">2. ... </span></li>\n</ul>','Strengths','','draft','open','open','','','','','2013-07-10 19:29:04','2013-07-10 19:29:04','',0,'http://vimbli.com/app/webroot/blog/?page_id=430',0,'page','',0),(431,1,'2013-07-10 19:22:08','2013-07-10 19:22:08','Several \"Strengths\" assessments exists.  We use a version of the strengths discussed in <a style=\"font-size: 16px;\" href=\"http://www.amazon.com/gp/product/0195167015?ie=UTF8&amp;tag=joyday-20&amp;linkCode=as2&amp;camp=1789&amp;creative=9325&amp;creativeASIN=0195167015\"> Character Strengths and Virtues</a> by Peterson and Seligman.\n\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">WISDOM &amp; KNOWLEDGE: Acquisition and use of knowledge</span>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Creativity [originality, ingenuity]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Curiosity [interest, novelty-seeking, openness to experience]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Open-mindedness [judgment, critical thinking]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Love of learning</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Perspective [wisdom]</span></li>\n</ul>\nCOURAGE: Accomplish goals\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Bravery [valor]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Persistence [perseverance, industriousness]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Integrity [authenticity, honesty]</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Vitality [zest, enthusiasm, vigor, energy]</span></li>\n</ul>\n<span style=\"font-size: small;\">HUMANITY: Tending and befriending others</span>\n<div>\n<ul>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Love</span></li>\n	<li><span style=\"font-size: small;\">Kindness [generosity, nurturance, care, compassion, altruistic love, \"n